%h1 Environment Variables

%p
  When building web applications usually the same application needs to work
  in different environments (development, staging, production). There are some
  %a(href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable")
    variables
  like API endpoints that differ depending on the environment.

%p
  Mint offers a simple feature for managing these variables. You can create
  different files
  %code .env
  and
  %code .env.production
  which have contents like this:

%pre
  %code.plaintext
    :escaped
      ENDPOINT=http://localhost:3001
      WSENDPOINT=ws://localhost:3001

%p
  Then in Mint code you can inline them:

%pre
  %code
    :escaped
      component Main {
        fun render : Html {
          <div>
            <{ @ENDPOINT }>
          </div>
        }
      }

%h2 Specifying .env file

%p
  %a(href="/guide/getting-started/using-the-cli")
    The Mint CLI
  has a global flag
  %code -e
  or
  %code --env
  which takes the path to the
  %code .env
  file:

%pre
  %code.plaintext
    :escaped
      mint start --env .env.production

